ey, New York; Isley, A.E., Hydrothermal plumes and the delivery of iron to BIF (1995) J. Geol., 103, pp. 169-185; Isley, A.E., Abbott, D.H., Plume-related mafic volcanism and the deposition of banded iron formation (1999) J. Geophys. Res., 104 (15), pp. 461-477; Jahren, A.H., The biochemicial consequences of the Mid-Cretaceous superplume (2002) J. Geodynamics, 34, pp. 177-191; Jahren, A.H., Terrestrial record of methane hydrate in the Early Cretaceous (2001) Geology, 29, pp. 159-162; Jenkyns, H.C., Cretaceous anoxic events: From continents to oceans (1980) J. Geol. Soc. London, 137, pp. 171-188; Kerr, A.C., Lithospheric thinning during the evolution of continental large igneous provinces (1994) Geology, 22, pp. 1027-1030; Kerr, A.C., Oceanic plateau formation: A cause of mass extinction and black shale deposition around the Cenomanian-Turonian boundary (1998) J. Geol. Soc. London, 155, pp. 619-626; Klein, C., Beukes, N.J., Time distribution, stratigraphy, and sedimentologic setting and geochemistry of Precambrian iron formations (1992) The Proterozoic Biosphere: A Multidisciplinary Study, pp. 139-146. , Cambridge University Press, New York; Kvenvolden, K.A., Potential effects of gas hydrate on human welfare (1999) Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA, 96, pp. 3420-3426; Larsen, T.B., Yuen, D.A., Fast plumeheads: Temperature-dependent versus non-Newtonian rheology (1997) Geophys. Res. Lett., 24, pp. 1995-1998; Larson, R.L., Geological consequences of superplumes (1991) Geology, 19, pp. 963-966; Larson, R.L., Kincaid, C., Onset of mid-Cretaceous volcanism by elevation of the 670 km thermal boundary layer (1996) Geology, 24, pp. 551-554; Lithgow-Bertelloni, C., Silver, P.G., Dynamic topography (1998) Nature, 395, pp. 269-272; Lowman, J.P., Jarvis, G.T., Continental collisions in wide aspect ratio and high Rayleigh number two-dimensional mantle convection models (1996) J. Geophys. Res., 101 (25), pp. 485-497; Lowman, J.P., Gable, C.W., Thermal evolution of the mantle following co